      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level for MRL 3.",
      "rationale": "ANSYS Fluent 2022R2 is used under a documented software quality plan that includes version control, regression testing, and release qualification records. The solver is FDA-recognized and has been used in multiple 510(k) submissions. Achieved level 3 reflects documented SQA procedures with traceability to simulation outputs."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level for MRL 3.",
      "rationale": "Code verification was performed using the Method of Manufactured Solutions for the incompressible Navier-Stokes solver. Observed order of convergence (1.97) is consistent with the theoretical second-order accuracy of the discretization scheme. Results documented in internal verification report CVL-VER-2024-03."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level for MRL 3.",
      "rationale": "A three-level mesh refinement study was conducted following ASME V&V 20 guidelines. The Grid Convergence Index (GCI) for the relative hemolysis index was 2.1% on the fine mesh, falling within the accepted threshold of 5%. The production mesh (8.4 million polyhedral cells) was selected based on this analysis."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level for MRL 3.",
      "rationale": "Experimental validation tests were conducted at the same five flow-speed operating points (2–6 L/min, 2000–4000 RPM) as the CFD simulations. Temperature, fluid viscosity (bovine blood, 37°C), and hematocrit (40%) were controlled and documented per ASTM F1841. Test conditions are representative of CPB clinical use."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level for MRL 3.",
      "rationale": "CFD-predicted normalized index of hemolysis (NIH) values were compared against experimental measurements at all five operating points. The mean relative error was 8.3% and the maximum was 14.1%. Agreement is within the validation uncertainty budget established in the validation plan. Bland-Altman analysis confirms no systematic bias."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level for MRL 3.",
      "rationale": "The primary quantity of interest — the relative hemolysis index RH — is directly linked to the regulatory acceptance criterion (RH < 1 vs. predicate). The hemolysis power-law model (Giersiepen-Wurzinger) is applied to shear stress and exposure time fields, both of which are outputs of the CFD solver. QoI relevance is high and well-documented."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level for MRL 3.",
      "rationale": "Validation experiments used the FDA generic centrifugal pump geometry, which is the same geometry simulated. Operating conditions span the clinical CPB envelope. While bovine blood was used in place of human blood (a recognized limitation), this is standard practice per FDA guidance and does not materially affect the hemolysis index comparison."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level for MRL 3.",
      "rationale": "Iterative convergence was monitored via residual norms and mass flux imbalance. All simulations achieved residuals below 1e-5 for continuity and momentum equations. Mass flux imbalance was below 0.01% in all cases. Pseudo-transient ramping was used to avoid solver divergence at high rotational speeds."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level for MRL 3.",
      "rationale": "Simulation setup was performed by a credentialed CFD analyst with 8 years of cardiovascular device experience. An independent peer review of the simulation setup, boundary conditions, and post-processing scripts was completed prior to results submission. Setup checklist and review records are retained in the project QMS."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level for MRL 3.",
      "rationale": "The SST k-omega turbulence model was selected based on its established performance for rotating machinery flows with adverse pressure gradients. The Giersiepen-Wurzinger hemolysis power law was chosen as the most widely validated model for CFD-based blood damage prediction. Model form choices are documented with supporting literature references."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level for MRL 3.",
      "rationale": "Pump geometry was derived from FDA-published CAD files (v1.3). Fluid properties (density 1050 kg/m3, dynamic viscosity 0.0035 Pa·s) are consistent with published values for human blood at 37°C and 40% hematocrit. Rotational speed and flow rate boundary conditions were set to match experimental test conditions with uncertainty bounds documented."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level for MRL 3.",
      "rationale": "Experimental hemolysis measurements were obtained from three independent test runs at each operating point using fresh bovine blood from the same supplier lot. Statistical analysis confirmed repeatability (CV < 8% across replicates). Sample size and preparation protocols are documented in the test report CVL-TEST-2024-07."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "not-assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Not evaluated; the assessment team determined that this factor does not apply to a purely computational sensitivity study in which all input parameters are directly specified from controlled experimental conditions without interpolation or surrogate mapping.",
      "rationale": "The equivalency of input parameters factor was not assessed. The team's position is that because all CFD boundary conditions were taken directly from the experimental test matrix without any surrogate or transfer function, there is no 'equivalency' question to evaluate — the inputs are identical by construction. This factor is therefore considered outside the scope of the present COU. No formal scoping or inapplicability determination was recorded in the credibility assessment plan; the factor simply was not included in the assessment workflow."
    }
